[stdout] {"type":"step_start","timestamp":1772768346117,"sessionID":"ses_33ec5cc26ffeXKbgVA6QpkLnH3","part":{"id":"prt_cc13a40030012NIzMIfy4I53V2","sessionID":"ses_33ec5cc26ffeXKbgVA6QpkLnH3","messageID":"msg_cc13a398f001dUgYY6kc4eUUxp","type":"step-start"}}

[stdout] {"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772768346134,"sessionID":"ses_33ec5cc26ffeXKbgVA6QpkLnH3","part":{"id":"prt_cc13a4005001Ad6TFMBmZiadwg","sessionID":"ses_33ec5cc26ffeXKbgVA6QpkLnH3","messageID":"msg_cc13a398f001dUgYY6kc4eUUxp","type":"tool","callID":"call_ONSAMNxXzyIheJZPljwtnrBt","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/SYNTAX.md","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/SYNTAX.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # tscircuit syntax primer\n2: \n3: ## 1) Root element\n4: \n5: A circuit is typically a default export that returns a `<board />` or a form-factor board component from `@tscircuit/common`.\n6: \n7: Example:\n8: \n9: ```tsx\n10: import React from \"react\"\n11: \n12: export default () => (\n13:   <board width=\"10mm\" height=\"10mm\">\n14:     <resistor name=\"R1\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" />\n15:   </board>\n16: )\n17: ```\n18: \n19: ## 2) Layout properties\n20: \n21: You can place nearly any element with:\n22: - `pcbX`, `pcbY` (PCB position)\n23: - `pcbRotation`\n24: - `layer` (e.g., `\"bottom\"`)\n25: \n26: For schematics:\n27: - `schX`, `schY`\n28: - `schRotation`\n29: - `schOrientation`\n30: \n31: Units\n32: - Numbers are interpreted as mm.\n33: - Strings can include units (e.g., `\"0.1in\"`, `\"2.54mm\"`).\n34: \n35: ## 3) Pin labels with `pinLabels`\n36: \n37: Use `pinLabels` to map physical pin numbers to meaningful names. This is essential for chips and ICs.\n38: \n39: ```tsx\n40: <chip\n41:   name=\"U1\"\n42:   footprint=\"qfp32\"\n43:   pinLabels={{\n44:     pin1: [\"GP0\", \"SPI0_RX\", \"I2C0_SDA\", \"UART0_TX\"],\n45:     pin2: [\"GP1\", \"SPI0_CS\", \"I2C0_SCL\", \"UART0_RX\"],\n46:     pin3: \"GND\",\n47:     // ...\n48:   }}\n49: />\n50: ```\n51: \n52: With multi-alias, any of the names can be used in traces:\n53: \n54: ```tsx\n55: <trace from=\"U1.GP0\" to=\"U2.SDA\" />\n56: <trace from=\"U1.SPI0_RX\" to=\"U3.MISO\" />\n57: ```\n58: \n59: ## 4) Pin attributes with `pinAttributes`\n60: \n61: Use `pinAttributes` to add semantic metadata to pins. This enables DRC checks, schematic arrows, and board-level pinout exposure.\n62: \n63: Example using a 555 timer (NE555):\n64: \n65: ```tsx\n66: <chip\n67:   name=\"U1\"\n68:   footprint=\"dip8\"\n69:   pinLabels={{\n70:     pin1: \"GND\",\n71:     pin2: \"TRIG\",\n72:     pin3: \"OUT\",\n73:     pin4: \"RESET\",\n74:     pin5: \"CTRL\",\n75:     pin6: \"THRES\",\n76:     pin7: \"DISCH\",\n77:     pin8: \"VCC\",\n78:   }}\n79:   pinAttributes={{\n80:     VCC: { requiresPower: true },\n81:     RESET: { mustBeConnected: true },\n82:   }}\n83: />\n84: ```\n85: \n86: Available attributes:\n87: \n88: | Attribute | Type | Description |\n89: |-----------|------|-------------|\n90: | `requiresPower` | boolean | Signal goes INTO the chip (shows input arrow on schematic) |\n91: | `providesPower` | boolean | Signal comes OUT of the chip (shows output arrow on schematic) |\n92: | `mustBeConnected` | boolean | DRC error if this pin is left floating |\n93: | `includeInBoardPinout` | boolean | Expose this pin to the board-level pinout |\n94: \n95: ## 5) Type-safe chip components\n96: \n97: For reusable chip components, define `pinLabels` as a const and use `ChipProps` for type safety:\n98: \n99: ```tsx\n100: import type { ChipProps } from \"tscircuit\"\n101: \n102: const pinLabels = {\n103:   pin1: \"VCC\",\n104:   pin2: \"GND\",\n105:   pin3: [\"SDA\", \"I2C_DATA\"],\n106:   pin4: [\"SCL\", \"I2C_CLK\"],\n107: } as const\n108: \n109: export const MyChip = (props: ChipProps<typeof pinLabels>) => (\n110:   <chip\n111:     {...props}\n112:     pinLabels={pinLabels}\n113:     footprint=\"soic4\"\n114:   />\n115: )\n116: ```\n117: \n118: ## 6) Connectivity with `<trace />`\n119: \n120: Connect pins with port selectors:\n121: \n122: ```tsx\n123: <trace from=\"R1.pin1\" to=\"C1.pin1\" />\n124: ```\n125: \n126: Connect to named nets. Net names must start with a letter or underscore and can only contain letters, numbers and underscores. \n127: \n128: ```tsx\n129: <trace from=\"U1.pin1\" to=\"net.GND\" />\n130: <trace from=\"U1.pin8\" to=\"net.VCC\" />\n131: <trace from=\"U1.pin8\" to=\"net.V3_3\" />\n132: ```\n133: \n134: Pin labels (in `pinLabels`) can contain letters, numbers, and underscores. Unlike net names, pin labels **can** start with a number (e.g., `\"3V3\"` is valid).\n135: \n136: Useful trace props (optional)\n137: - `width` / `thickness`\n138: - `minLength` / `maxLength`\n139: \n140: ## 7) Grouping for PCB layout\n141: \n142: Use `<group />` like a container to move/layout parts together.\n143: \n144: ```tsx\n145: <board width=\"20mm\" height=\"20mm\">\n146:   <group pcbX={5} pcbY={5}>\n147:     <resistor name=\"R1\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" pcbX={2.5} pcbY={2.5} />\n148:     <resistor name=\"R2\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" pcbX={2.5} pcbY={0} />\n149:     <resistor name=\"R3\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" pcbX={2.5} pcbY={-2.5} />\n150:   </group>\n151: </board>\n152: ```\n153: \n154: ## 8) Schematic pin arrangement\n155: \n156: Control how pins appear on the schematic symbol with `schPinArrangement`:\n157: \n158: ```tsx\n159: <chip\n160:   name=\"U1\"\n161:   footprint=\"soic16\"\n162:   pinLabels={{\n163:     pin1: \"VCC1\",\n164:     pin2: \"IN1\",\n165:     pin3: \"IN2\",\n166:     pin4: \"IN3\",\n167:     pin5: \"IN4\",\n168:     pin6: \"GND1\",\n169:     pin7: \"GND2\",\n170:     pin8: \"VCC2\",\n171:     pin9: \"OUT1\",\n172:     pin10: \"OUT2\",\n173:     pin11: \"OUT3\",\n174:     pin12: \"OUT4\",\n175:   }}\n176:   schPinArrangement={{\n177:     topSide: { pins: [\"VCC1\", \"VCC2\"], direction: \"left-to-right\" },\n178:     bottomSide: { pins: [\"GND1\", \"GND2\"], direction: \"left-to-right\" },\n179:     leftSide: { pins: [\"IN1\", \"IN2\", \"IN3\", \"IN4\"], direction: \"top-to-bottom\" },\n180:     rightSide: { pins: [\"OUT1\", \"OUT2\", \"OUT3\", \"OUT4\"], direction: \"top-to-bottom\" },\n181:   }}\n182: />\n183: ```\n184: \n185: Available sides: `leftSide`, `rightSide`, `topSide`, `bottomSide`\n186: - Left/right sides use `direction: \"top-to-bottom\"` or `\"bottom-to-top\"`\n187: - Top/bottom sides use `direction: \"left-to-right\"` or `\"right-to-left\"`\n188: \n189: ## 9) Manufacturing helpers\n190: \n191: For turnkey assembly you will often want:\n192: - `supplierPartNumbers` (pin a specific supplier SKU/part number)\n193: - `doNotPlace` (exclude from automated placement)\n194: \n195: Example:\n196: \n197: ```tsx\n198: <capacitor\n199:   name=\"C1\"\n200:   capacitance=\"100nF\"\n201:   footprint=\"0402\"\n202:   supplierPartNumbers={{ jlcpcb: \"C14663\" }}\n203: />\n204: \n205: <resistor name=\"R1\" resistance=\"10k\" footprint=\"0402\" doNotPlace />\n206: ```\n\n(End of file - total 206 lines)\n</content>","title":"workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/SYNTAX.md","metadata":{"preview":"# tscircuit syntax primer\n\n## 1) Root element\n\nA circuit is typically a default export that returns a `<board />` or a form-factor board component from `@tscircuit/common`.\n\nExample:\n\n```tsx\nimport React from \"react\"\n\nexport default () => (\n  <board width=\"10mm\" height=\"10mm\">\n    <resistor name=\"R1\" resistance=\"1k\" footprint=\"0402\" />\n  </board>\n)\n```\n\n## 2) Layout properties\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772768346121,"end":1772768346134}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}}}}

[stdout] {"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772768346185,"sessionID":"ses_33ec5cc26ffeXKbgVA6QpkLnH3","part":{"id":"prt_cc13a400b0014YtZigik1vEg8r","sessionID":"ses_33ec5cc26ffeXKbgVA6QpkLnH3","messageID":"msg_cc13a398f001dUgYY6kc4eUUxp","type":"tool","callID":"call_5s7sknFoQwDju80bASqvirgd","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/CLI.md","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/CLI.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # tsci CLI primer\n2: \n3: Prereqs\n4: - Node.js or Bun\n5: - Install the tscircuit CLI (global install):\n6:   - npm: `npm install -g tscircuit`\n7:   - bun: `bun install --global tscircuit`\n8: \n9: Core commands\n10: \n11: 1) Create / bootstrap a project\n12: - `tsci init` (interactive)\n13: - `tsci init -y` (accept defaults)\n14: \n15: Typical output includes:\n16: - `index.tsx` (main circuit entrypoint)\n17: - `package.json`, `tsconfig.json`\n18: - `tscircuit.config.json`\n19: \n20: 2) Preview locally (interactive)\n21: - `tsci dev`\n22: - Opens a local preview server (commonly https://localhost:3020)\n23: - Note: For AI-driven iteration, prefer `tsci build` over `tsci dev`—dev mode is primarily for interactive visual feedback.\n24: \n25: 3) Search the ecosystem\n26: - `tsci search \"<query>\"`\n27:   - Finds footprints, components, and packages across multiple sources\n28: \n29: Search flags:\n30: - `--jlcpcb` (or `--lcsc`) – Search JLCPCB/LCSC components by name or part number\n31: - `--kicad` – Search KiCad footprint library\n32: - `--tscircuit` – Search tscircuit registry packages\n33: \n34: Examples:\n35: ```bash\n36: # Search JLCPCB for microcontrollers\n37: tsci search --jlcpcb \"ATmega328\"\n38: # Output: ATMEGA328P-AU (C14877) - stock: 20,226\n39: \n40: # Search JLCPCB by part number\n41: tsci search --jlcpcb \"C14877\"\n42: \n43: # Search for USB-C connectors on JLCPCB\n44: tsci search --jlcpcb \"USB-C 16pin\"\n45: \n46: # Search KiCad footprints\n47: tsci search --kicad \"QFP-32\"\n48: # Output: kicad:Package_QFP/LQFP-32_5x5mm_P0.5mm\n49: \n50: # Search KiCad for SMD resistor footprints\n51: tsci search --kicad \"0402\"\n52: \n53: # Search tscircuit registry for existing projects\n54: tsci search --tscircuit \"LED\"\n55: # Output: seveibar/usb-c-flashlight - Stars: 5\n56: \n57: # Search without flags (searches all sources)\n58: tsci search \"ESP32\"\n59: ```\n60: \n61: 4) Add existing registry packages to your project\n62: - `tsci add <author/pkg>`\n63:   - Use when a reusable tscircuit package already exists in the registry\n64:   - Example: `tsci add seveibar/PICO_W`\n65:   - Imports look like: `import { PICO_W } from \"@tsci/seveibar.PICO_W\"`\n66:   - The `@tsci/` scope with dot notation (`author.pkg`) is the registry convention\n67: \n68: 5) Import components (e.g., from JLCPCB)\n69: - `tsci import <query>`\n70:   - Use when you need to bring a specific part into your project\n71:   - Searches both the tscircuit registry and JLCPCB parts database\n72:   - Opens an interactive picker to select and import the component\n73: \n74: Workflow:\n75: ```bash\n76: # First, search to find the part number\n77: tsci search --jlcpcb \"ATmega328\"\n78: # Output: ATMEGA328P-AU (C14877) - stock: 20,226\n79: \n80: # Then import using the part number or name\n81: tsci import \"C14877\"\n82: # or\n83: tsci import \"ATmega328\"\n84: ```\n85: \n86: The interactive picker shows:\n87: - Registry packages (already wrapped by other users): `author/PART_NAME`\n88: - JLCPCB parts (raw import): `[jlcpcb] PART_NAME (CXXXXXX)`\n89: \n90: Tip: If someone has already imported the part, prefer the registry version—it may have better pin mappings or schematic symbols.\n91: \n92: 6) Build (generate circuit.json)\n93: \n94: Before building, it can be a good idea to check placement of the entire board or a specific component with `tsci check placement [file] [refdes]`\n95: \n96: - `tsci build` (auto-detects entrypoint)\n97: - `tsci build path/to/file.circuit.tsx`\n98: \n99: Notes\n100: - If no path is provided, `tsci build` searches for `index.tsx` or `mainEntrypoint` in `tscircuit.config.json`.\n101: - `*.circuit.tsx` files are built automatically.\n102: - Outputs go to `dist/`.\n103: \n104: Useful flags\n105: - `--ignore-errors` (CI/automation)\n106: - `--ignore-warnings`\n107: - `--all-images` (emit PCB/schematic/3D renders into `dist/`)\n108: \n109: DRC (Design Rule Check)\n110: - DRC errors are often reported but can frequently be ignored during development.\n111: - Focus on getting the circuit correct first; DRC violations can be addressed later when preparing for manufacturing.\n112: \n113: 7) Export (SVG/netlist/3D/library)\n114: - `tsci export <file> -f <format>`\n115: \n116: Common formats\n117: - `schematic-svg`\n118: - `pcb-svg`\n119: - `readable-netlist`\n120: - `specctra-dsn`\n121: - `gltf` / `glb`\n122: - `kicad-library`\n123: \n124: 8) Visual snapshots for analysis and verification\n125: - `tsci snapshot` generates visual outputs (schematic/PCB, optionally 3D) and writes/overwrites snapshots by default.\n126: - Use these visuals to inspect placement, orientation, and overall circuit understanding during iteration.\n127: - `tsci snapshot --test` switches to regression-test mode: it fails on visual diffs and does **not** overwrite snapshots.\n128: - `tsci snapshot --pcb-only` generates only PCB visuals, which is especially useful for placement-focused iteration.\n129: - `tsci snapshot --3d` includes 3D snapshots in the output.\n130: \n131: Recommended pattern:\n132: ```bash\n133: # During development: generate fresh visuals for analysis and review\n134: tsci snapshot\n135: \n136: # During placement-heavy iterations: focus only on PCB output\n137: tsci snapshot --pcb-only\n138: \n139: # In CI/regression checks: detect unexpected visual changes without overwriting\n140: tsci snapshot --test\n141: ```\n142: \n143: 9) Auth / publish\n144: - `tsci login` (browser-based)\n145: - `tsci push` (publish package)\n146: - `tsci auth print-token`\n147: \n148: Guidance\n149: - Prefer `tsci --help` and `tsci <cmd> --help` when unsure about flags.\n150: - Avoid `tsci push` unless the user explicitly asks to publish.\n\n(End of file - total 150 lines)\n</content>","title":"workspace/.claude/skills/tscircuit/CLI.md","metadata":{"preview":"# tsci CLI primer\n\nPrereqs\n- Node.js or Bun\n- Install the tscircuit CLI (global install):\n  - npm: `npm install -g tscircuit`\n  - bun: `bun install --global tscircuit`\n\nCore commands\n\n1) Create / bootstrap a project\n- `tsci init` (interactive)\n- `tsci init -y` (accept defaults)\n\nTypical output includes:\n- `index.tsx` (main circuit entrypoint)\n- `package.json`, `tsconfig.json`\n- `tscircuit.config.json`\n\n2) Preview locally (interactive)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772768346130,"end":1772768346179}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}}}}

